00:43.380 --> 00:51.840
This is David Cruz and Bill Vernon. Practicing physicist Robert L. Forward is
also a science fiction writer. After writing science fact articles in the

00:51.840 --> 00:59.640
magazines for almost 20 years, Forward recently published his first science
fiction novel, Dragon's Egg. When we asked Forward how he began writing science

00:59.640 --> 01:09.420
fiction, he claimed he was tricked into doing it. But the way I got into
actually writing fiction was Larry Niven tricked me. Here he explains how he

01:09.420 --> 01:20.920
innocently offered to help Larry Niven. Larry Niven and Jerry Pornell were
running a lecture series at UCLA, invited me to come and give a scientific talk

01:20.920 --> 01:35.200
on gravity as part of their series. It was how science fiction and science
interact. And at the close of one of the sessions that Larry was talking on, he

01:35.200 --> 01:46.580
said he wanted to write a story about beings that lived on a neutron star. Frank
Drake had mentioned this idea a number of years before. He said he really wanted

01:46.580 --> 01:54.020
to write that story. And that night at the cocktail party that they threw, I
said, Larry, I'll tell you what I'll do. I will work up all the scientific

01:54.020 --> 02:03.900
details behind the story because I know a lot about neutron star physics. And it
would be a fun story to read, and I'd like to read hard science fiction. And

02:03.900 --> 02:12.600
what I'd like to do is give you enough facts so that you can write a really hard
science fiction story without too many errors in it. When Ford finished his

02:12.600 --> 02:21.820
part, Niven was still busy, so Ford continued the work himself. And so I worked
up all the science and gave him about 25, 30 pages of notes. And he said, gee,

02:22.000 --> 02:32.440
I'm busy right now working with Jerry Pornell on something called Lucifer's
Hammer. And I'm pretty busy. I'll tell you what we'll do. Why don't we just sort

02:32.440 --> 02:43.620
of make this a collaboration. You write the first draft of the story. And then
I'll take it over from there and rewrite the thing because you're not a writer,

02:43.640 --> 02:52.480
and I am. And that way we'll get the best of both worlds. Well, so I went back
and wrote the first draft. And when I came back, he was still busy. And so I

02:52.480 --> 03:02.480
ended up finding out that I wanted to read this story. And the only way I could
read that story was to write it first. So I had to write it. And so Larry Niven

03:02.480 --> 03:04.320
tricked me into getting into science fiction.

03:14.640 --> 03:23.560
But Larry Niven didn't abandon Ford after tricking him into writing a novel. He
advised Ford on many aspects, including a major plot element. Larry Niven

03:23.560 --> 03:32.580
basically gave the thousand to one, I mean, excuse me, the million to one time
difference.

03:35.780 --> 03:47.320
And the main thing that he brought out was the fact that the important part of
the story was not all the science, which would have been my tendency to write,

03:47.320 --> 04:04.320
but the problems of how do you communicate with somebody that lives and dies a
million times faster than you do. And if those beings, since they would be

04:04.320 --> 04:13.920
thinking a million times faster than you, would figure out that you were there
long before you could figure out they were there, and they had to figure out a

04:13.920 --> 04:26.660
way to communicate with you and signal you that they were there before you left.
And so he mentioned the fact that, for instance, somebody on the neutron star

04:26.660 --> 04:39.180
would have to climb a mountain and send a signal. And that might take them many
generations. Actually, in the story, I compressed it into one generation,

04:39.340 --> 04:50.680
basically. But that was the kind of attitude that he brought toward the story
that helped a lot. More on Robert Ford tomorrow.

