06:25.280 --> 06:32.800
This is Bill Vernon. And David Cruz. In our last show, we learned how Robert
Ford was tricked into writing the manuscript, which evolved into his novel,

06:32.960 --> 06:42.800
Dragon's Egg. Larry Niven helped Ford flesh out his ideas, but it was Lester Del
Rey who helped him polish the manuscript into a novel. My very first draft, of

06:42.800 --> 07:01.280
course, was quite rough from a writing point of view. And when Lester looked at
it, he saw some potential in it, but as it was, as the manuscript was sent to

07:01.280 --> 07:19.800
him, it wasn't acceptable. It wasn't the book. And he sat down and typed up 14
pages, single space of detailed criticism of the manuscript. And those 14 pages,

07:20.040 --> 07:32.000
when I followed them to the letter, and I don't think I disagreed with him on
but, say, one or two things, when I went back through the manuscript and took

07:32.000 --> 07:47.160
his suggestions and then looked at the resultants, it was, you know, it began to
be readable instead of being a, well, a science fact article, I guess. You know,

07:47.220 --> 07:49.560
it had some flow. It had some characterization.

07:52.360 --> 08:01.760
But, you know, it still was a hard science fiction novel. In Dragon's Egg, Ford
takes a hard science approach to a situation in which beings who inhabit a

08:01.760 --> 08:09.540
neutron star learn of the humans who are orbiting their star, then establish
communications with them. The task is made difficult, though, by the fact that

08:09.540 --> 08:18.140
the aliens live at a pace roughly a million times faster than that of humans.
Thus, an individual alien, or chela, lives out its entire life in several human

08:18.140 --> 08:26.720
minutes. The chela, being native to a neutron star, with its intense
gravitational and magnetic fields and extremely dense matter, are certainly

08:26.720 --> 08:39.180
constructed different from humans. Here, Ford tells us about the aliens, their
environment, and their names. Once I had placed my imagination and myself on the

08:39.180 --> 08:53.420
surface of the neutron star, now, once I knew the territory well enough and
appreciated the fact that the light on this star comes from below, not above, so

08:53.420 --> 09:05.120
if the sky is black, there's no light coming out of it except the two stars,
everything is aglow from below, and the territory is very flat because of the

09:05.120 --> 09:25.200
terrific gravity, I began to sort of appreciate what it was like there. And what
I basically did was take the Indian technique of naming children about things

09:25.200 --> 09:37.240
that occurred shortly after they were born and applied it to the chela, but put
in a hyphen, so it would take out the Indian context, and also, of course, a lot

09:37.240 --> 09:49.760
of the Indian things like eagles and feathers and sky and things like that don't
exist, so I had to do that transfer. The chela's social structure differs from

09:49.760 --> 10:00.540
ours as well, though there are some similarities. Soon I began to realize that
in my dreaming up of these creatures, I had ended up with a social structure

10:00.540 --> 10:15.780
that was sort of halfway between a Scottish clan and an Indian tribe, and as if
both the Indians and the Scottish were crocodiles that laid eggs instead of

10:15.780 --> 10:26.440
having the problems of mammals that they have to take care of their young. The
young are immediately viable in crocodiles and turtles, and so are the little

10:26.440 --> 10:40.680
tiny chela. So what I tried to do was imagine what it would be like if instead
of monkeys developing intelligent social interactions, crocodiles developed

10:40.680 --> 10:42.680
intelligent social interactions.

