23:29.660 --> 23:38.560
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. Early in 1982, Norman Spinrad's science
fiction novel, The Iron Dream, was totally banned in Germany. As we explained

23:38.560 --> 23:45.660
last time, the book is an anti-fascist novel. Though Spinrad pretends the book
was written by Adolf Hitler, it is actually a brilliant criticism of the

23:45.660 --> 23:53.260
political and racial views held by Hitler. Spinrad says the book has been well
received in all the countries where it's been published. This book has been

23:53.260 --> 24:11.080
published now in the United States, Britain, France, Japan, Spain, Portugal,
Argentina, Italy, I forget where else, about eight different countries. It's

24:11.080 --> 24:24.460
been published in the other two Axis powers. It's been published in Argentina.
And it's been extensively reviewed in about eight different countries. I have no

24:24.460 --> 24:31.480
instance where the book was misunderstood and was taken as anything but an anti
-Nazi and anti-fascist novel

24:34.200 --> 24:42.680
throughout the world. The German censors cited the book's danger to young people
as one reason it was banned. We asked Spinrad if anyone could possibly

24:42.680 --> 24:53.720
misunderstand his intentions in The Iron Dream. Well, any, I mean, you know, you
know, you know, you know, Hinkley certainly misunderstood saying taxi drivers,

24:53.740 --> 25:01.200
so there's always schizophrenics and maniacs around who can misunderstand
anything. I mean, you know, David Horowitz heard demons in his head. I mean,

25:01.260 --> 25:09.380
there are always completely crazy people who can read things out of something
that were never in there. So I'd be one or two people around, you know,

25:10.200 --> 25:18.860
psychotics who could get anything out of any book. But I don't, I, see, the book
is written on two levels. The sophisticated readers, they understand what it is

25:18.860 --> 25:30.120
to begin with. But the other level is that the kind of people who are into
things like Perry Rodin and that kind of proto-fascist science fantasy would

25:30.120 --> 25:37.420
start off reading the book, maybe identifying with Ferrick Jagger, you know, a
third of the way into it or something, and suddenly realizing what it is they're

25:37.420 --> 25:45.120
identifying with. And so it becomes a kind of deprogramming experience for the
kind of people that they claim would be harmed. I think it would be a very

25:45.120 --> 25:54.440
strongly anti-Nazi book precisely for those kinds of young people who might have
leanings in that direction because they would then be confronted with what it is

25:54.440 --> 26:04.840
that they're really identifying with. We also asked Spinrad what his reaction to
the ban was. My reaction to the ban is very complicated. First of all, it took

26:04.840 --> 26:13.920
ten years to get this book published in Germany. All my French friends said it
would never be published in Germany. So when Heine Berlach, you know, summoned

26:13.920 --> 26:20.900
up the courage to publish it, I was very pleased, and I thought that this was
going to, you know, that this represented a kind of maturity on the part of

26:20.900 --> 26:28.360
Germany, that they're willing to look at this stuff. And I felt very good about
it being published there, and I was a bit surprised. Now that it's banned,

26:28.640 --> 26:39.580
obviously I feel that, well, the book says it all. The book itself, in a way, is
about why it was banned, because it's the same sort of mentality that goes

26:39.580 --> 26:50.520
around banning books that resulted in a different kind of way, in the Third
Reich. That's not to say that all Germans are like this, because the publisher

26:50.520 --> 26:58.780
has fought this all the way and is continuing to fight it. Most of the German
newspapers, there's been a lot of coverage, has supported the book against the

26:58.780 --> 27:08.640
ban. The German chapter of World SF had a vote and issued a public statement
against the ban in supporting the book.

27:11.400 --> 27:19.160
So, you know, I think it's a very retrogressive thing, and it says something
about, I suppose, the German political and social system, is that they do not

27:19.160 --> 27:27.480
understand the concept that is embodied in the First Amendment to the
Constitution of the United States. And it's a particularly pernicious law,

27:27.940 --> 27:36.480
because anything can be banned under this law under the grounds that it's not
fit for children, even if it's not intended for children, which is exactly the

27:36.480 --> 27:42.760
kind of thing that the moral majority is trying to do here, which tells you what
kind of people they are, too.

